Sleeping Talk
Some kids talk at night.
I don't mean those who wake up very excited telling us something that's happened the other day, but children who talk are sleeping.
The first time that happens to the best you take a breath, but it doesn't really matter.
It is a benign change in the dream that is called dreamy.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure more than one has been told that he spoke at night.
This phenomenon may appear very sporadic (once in life for example associated with a high fever episode), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month...), the child remembers nothing the next day.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance.
They often relate to other changes in sleep such as nightmares, night terrors, night enuresis (to sleep on the floor) or sonambulism, but it doesn't have to be that way.
As mentioned earlier, they can also be associated with very high fever patterns, stress situations, or overexit.
Anyway, it's a little studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also very variable.
I may speak in a quiet tone of voice, loose words, a murmur or everything else (grunts, lightnings, long speeches...).
In cases where the event is very intense, it is appropriate to observe the child and consult with a specialist, to check whether there is any question that is causing much anxiety and thus gives him a way out.
We have said that it is a benign change, so it has no treatment, unless you are associated with another change in the dream that can be treated (for example, if you are associated with sleep apnea or a stress picture).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child much before going to sleep.
So find quiet games and avoid TV programs or series that are scary or a little violent.
With very nervous children and which costs them a lot to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them acquire some inner calm.
This will help the child to have a quieter dream.
Once the dreams appear, try to keep calm.
Remember that they're harmless to the child and that the next day you won't remember anything about what happened.
Useful Councils
Don't wake him up.
It's useless, because he's not conscious, and you'll break his dream.
Although he's talking, he's sleeping and so he's resting.
Remember that if you show a lot of anxiety during several episodes, you should consult or find out what causes so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what you're saying (which is not the most common), don't fall into the temptation to question him for information.
You won't get anything, because when you're asleep, you're not aware of how to organize your thoughts.
In addition, you will hear what you say, but you do not know what you are dreaming to say that, with which you are very careful about how you interpret the information and the conclusions you come up with.
You never tell the child that you can question him at night to know his secrets.
Don't even joke.
That creates a lot of anxiety.
In short, don't worry, it's nothing bad, it's an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
