Psychology of Overlays: Why do we spend more money?
The participants in the auctions are willing to spend more money and overestimate the product.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York discovered the neurological - economic bases of this well-known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to the study published in Science magazine, people don't want to lose their skills like eBay's heels, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
Scientists have tried to establish the neurological scheme of this "game" by means of experimental substations.
One of the volunteer groups played the lottery, the other participated in a sub-accumulation and as long as it was examined through the functional magnetic resonance system (fMRI) the active areas of the brain of the participants in the experiment.
In both games the participants could earn money, but during the auctions, where it is essential to bet more than the other, by losing the game, the operation of the complex called strata located below the brain cortex was intensified.
This brain area, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the "auto premium" mechanism of the nervous system.
According to scientists, the increase in bets is explained as a prevention not to cause an intense reaction to the strata.
In order to justify their theory, the economists of the scientific group also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment, three groups objected to one person under different circumstances.
The control group was simply informed of the actual value of the product in question, and its members were betting.
In addition, another group was promised that if they won, they would receive $15 more.
On the other hand, the third group received exactly 15 dollars before the auction, but in the event of the auction loss, the members of the group lost even that money.
So the only difference between the two groups was that for one the triumph was highlighted and for the other the failure.
However, checking the hypothesis of neurologists, members of the group playing "against failure" were willing to bet even more than members of the control group and the "winner" group.
"These results cannot be deducted from any previously existing economic theory.
As those so far explained the phenomena of the auctions only with the joy of winning and with the prevention of risks.
Only visual neurological methods helped resolve this contradiction between the two theories, so that we now come to a third explanation" - established Andrew Schutter, professor of the University of New York Economics.
Hepatitis: When should you go to a doctor?
In the world some 50 million people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is considered one of the main causes of death.
The number of people infected in this country is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated because many of the sick do not know that they are infected.
The name of hepatitis is the common name of different liver diseases caused by the virus.
Symptoms appear to be very much; they are characteristic of liver and liver infection, but their pathogens and diseases are very different.
Hepatitis viruses, depending on the pathogen agent, are spread through two main forms: hepatitis A and E via food (e.g. with water or contaminated food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body humour (sperm, vaginal humour, salt).
It is recommended for travellers to be protected by a vaccine against virus A and B, against C no vaccines.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two or three weeks after consuming the infected food, it is manifested by a bad general condition, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After this appear in the skin and in the white of the eyes, it becomes clear, dark urine and healing can last even for two or three weeks.
Each year a million people die from cancer in the world and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that, according to estimates, only one in 10 people is treated pharmacologically.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can produce liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most infected people do not know that they are sick because this pathological agent gradually destroys the liver cells and often the first symptoms appear only 20-30 years later.
Therefore, early recognition, systematic medical control is very important.
This disease is much more common in three groups: people who had blood transfusions before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
There are currently about 200 million people in the world who suffer from chronic hepatitis C.
As this disease can also be detected with routine laboratory control, it is worth consulting with the family doctor when experiencing any unknown symptoms.
The disease has healing if it is detected in time, it is possible to eliminate the virus from the body, thereby eliminating the infection and preventing cancer.
On 30 September, it was the World Hepatitis Day, which was organized for the first time in 2004 by the organizations representing the sick.
Its aim is to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and to the importance of their early recognition.
